      <h2>Step 6: Evaluate Management</h2>
      <p>
        When you buy a stock, you are hiring the CEO and the management team to run the business for you. Evaluating management is more art than science, but it is crucial.
      </p>
      <p>
        Look for leaders who:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Have Skin in the Game:</strong> Does the CEO own a significant amount of the company's stock? If their wealth is tied to the stock price, their interests are aligned with yours.</li>
        <li><strong>Are Honest About Failures:</strong> Read the CEO's annual letter to shareholders. Great CEOs (like Warren Buffett) highlight their mistakes. Bad CEOs blame the economy, the weather, or "unprecedented headwinds" for poor performance.</li>
        <li><strong>Allocate Capital Wisely:</strong> The primary job of a CEO is capital allocation—deciding what to do with the cash the business generates. Do they make smart acquisitions? Do they buy back stock when it is cheap? Or do they engage in "empire building" by buying irrelevant companies just to make themselves look more important?</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Pros and Cons of Picking Individual Stocks</h2>
      <p>
        Before you decide to build a portfolio of individual stocks, it is vital to understand the trade-offs compared to simply buying an index fund (which guarantees you the <a href="/average-stock-market-return">average stock market return</a>).
      </p>

      <div class="pros-cons">
        <div class="pros">
          <h4>The Pros of Stock Picking</h4>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Potential for Outperformance:</strong> If you pick the right companies, you can significantly beat the market average. Finding one "multi-bagger" (a stock that goes up 10x or 20x) can change your financial life.</li>
            <li><strong>Control:</strong> You decide exactly what you own. You can avoid industries you dislike (like tobacco or fossil fuels) and concentrate your money in your highest-conviction ideas.</li>
            <li><strong>Intellectual Satisfaction:</strong> Researching companies, understanding their business models, and seeing your thesis play out is deeply rewarding for those who enjoy the process.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="cons">
          <h4>The Cons of Stock Picking</h4>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>High Risk of Underperformance:</strong> The harsh reality is that most professional fund managers fail to beat the S&P 500 over a 10-year period. If professionals struggle, amateurs face an uphill battle.</li>
            <li><strong>Time-Consuming:</strong> Properly analyzing a stock takes dozens of hours of reading annual reports, listening to earnings calls, and building valuation models. It is a part-time job.</li>
            <li><strong>Emotional Stress:</strong> When you own an index fund and it drops 20%, you know the whole market is down. When you own a single stock and it drops 20% while the market is up, it is incredibly stressful. You must constantly decide whether to sell, hold, or buy more. If you struggle with this, you might need to read our guide on <a href="/how-to-sell-stocks">how to sell stocks</a>.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>Common Misconceptions About Stock Picking</h2>

      <h3>Misconception 1: "A low share price means the stock is cheap."</h3>
      <p>
        This is the most dangerous trap for beginners. A stock trading at $2 is not inherently cheaper than a stock trading at $2,000.
      </p>
      <p>
        The price of a single share is completely arbitrary. It is determined by the total value of the company divided by the number of shares outstanding. A $2 stock might belong to a failing company with billions of shares outstanding and massive debt, making it wildly overvalued. A $2,000 stock might belong to an incredibly profitable, growing company with very few shares outstanding, making it a bargain.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you want to understand how companies manipulate their share price without changing the value of the business, try experimenting with our <a href="/stock-split-calculator">stock split calculator</a>.
      </p>

      <h3>Misconception 2: "I need inside information to win."</h3>
      <p>
        You do not need to know a secret to make money in the stock market. In fact, trading on non-public, material information is a federal crime (insider trading).
      </p>
      <p>
        The edge in investing does not come from having better information; it comes from having better behavior. Wall Street is obsessed with what a company will earn in the next 90 days. If you are willing to look out 3 to 5 years, you have a massive advantage over the hyper-active professionals who are forced to chase short-term performance.
      </p>

      <h3>Misconception 3: "Stock picking is the same as day trading."</h3>
      <p>
        Stock picking (investing) and day trading are polar opposites.
      </p>
      <p>
        Day trading is attempting to profit from minute-by-minute price movements based on technical charts and momentum. It is a zero-sum game played against high-frequency trading algorithms. If you want to know <a href="/how-to-trade-stocks">how to trade stocks</a>, be prepared for a highly stressful, statistically difficult endeavor.
      </p>
      <p>
        Stock picking, as we have discussed, is buying a piece of a business because you believe in its long-term cash-generating potential. You buy it and ideally do nothing for years.
      </p>

      <h2>The "Core and Explore" Strategy</h2>
      <p>
        For most investors, the optimal approach to stock picking is not an all-or-nothing decision. You do not have to choose between putting 100% of your money in index funds or 100% of your money in individual stocks.
      </p>
      <p>
        Many successful investors use the <strong>"Core and Explore"</strong> strategy:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>The Core (80% - 90% of your portfolio):</strong> This money is invested in low-cost, broadly diversified index funds (like an S&P 500 ETF). This guarantees that the bulk of your wealth grows steadily with the overall market.</li>
        <li><strong>The Explore (10% - 20% of your portfolio):</strong> This is your "stock picking" money. You use this portion to buy individual companies you have deeply researched. If your picks do well, they boost your overall returns. If you are wrong, the damage is contained to a small portion of your net worth, and your index funds will carry you through.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Conclusion: Your Next Steps</h2>
      <p>
        Learning how to pick stocks is a lifelong journey. It requires patience, discipline, and a willingness to read dense financial documents.
      </p>
      <p>
        If you are ready to start, do not begin by buying shares. Begin by paper trading. Track a portfolio of 5 companies you believe are excellent businesses. Write down exactly <em>why</em> you are "buying" them—what is their moat, what is their valuation, and what is your thesis for their future growth. Check back in a year. Did your thesis play out?
      </p>
      <p>
        Remember, the stock market is a device for transferring money from the impatient to the patient. Do your research, buy wonderful businesses at fair prices, and let the compounding magic happen.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>How do I know if a stock is overvalued or undervalued?</summary>
        <p>Valuation is determined by comparing a company's stock price to its underlying financial metrics. The most common tool is the Price-to-Earnings (P/E) ratio, which compares the stock price to the company's earnings per share. If a company's P/E ratio is significantly higher than its historical average or its industry peers, it may be overvalued. Other metrics include Price-to-Free Cash Flow and the PEG ratio.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Should beginners pick individual stocks?</summary>
        <p>Most financial experts recommend that beginners start by investing the vast majority of their money in broad market index funds or ETFs. This provides instant diversification and lowers risk. Picking individual stocks requires significant time to research financial statements and understand business models. If a beginner wants to pick stocks, they should limit it to 5% to 10% of their total portfolio.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What makes a good stock to buy for the long term?</summary>
        <p>A great long-term stock typically belongs to a company with a strong "economic moat" (a sustainable competitive advantage), a solid balance sheet with manageable debt, consistent free cash flow generation, and an honest, capable management team. The goal is to find a business that will be significantly larger and more profitable 10 years from now.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How many stocks should I own to be diversified?</summary>
        <p>If you are building a portfolio of individual stocks, owning between 15 and 30 carefully selected companies across different sectors is generally considered sufficient to achieve most the benefits of diversification. Owning too few stocks exposes you to massive single-company risk, while owning too many makes it impossible to properly monitor all your investments.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>When is the right time to sell a stock I picked?</summary>
        <p>You should consider selling a stock when the fundamental thesis for why you bought it is no longer true. This could be because the company's competitive advantage has eroded, management has made poor decisions, or the valuation has become so detached from reality that the risk outweighs the reward. You should generally not sell a stock simply because the price temporarily dropped during a broader market correction.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

